<br>
Energia strap-on ( they used 4 to lift the Buran)<br>
Gross Mass: 355,000 kg.<br>
Empty Mass: 35,000 kg. <br>
Thrust (vac): 806,200 kgf.<br>
Isp: 337 sec.<br>
Burn time: 145 sec. <br>
Throttleable: yes<br>
Mass Ratio 10.1 to 1<br>
Thrust to weight ratio at liftoff 2.27 to 1<br>
<br>
Thoikol Shuttle SRB’s<br>
Gross Mass: 589,670 kg. <br>
Empty Mass: 86,183 kg. <br>
Thrust (vac): 1,174,713 kgf.<br>
Isp: 269 sec.<br>
Burn time: 124 sec. <br>
Throttleable: no<br>
Mass Ratio 6.84 to 1<br>
Thrust to weight ratio at liftoff 2 to 1<br>
<br>
I for one think its insane to use engines that you can’t control. Sure the propellant grain is made so that the thrust is relatively constant but once ignited the only controls you have are thrust termination and then separation.<br>
<br>
In the book “Countdown to Disaster”  the author quotes Ken Mattingly who said words to the effect,<br>
<br>
‘The scariest moment in my life was just prior to ignition of the SRB's. knowing that just a 1 second offset in the ignition and thrust build up of those monsters would cause the thrust to be so asymmetrical  that the whole stack would cartwheel into the Florida swamps.’<br>
<br>
And<br>
<br>
‘When those solids are burning the ride is so rough that its amazing that the whole thing doesn’t fall apart.’<br>
<br>
As far as Orion tossing HLLV’s based on  the shuttles SRB’s give me a break. Just imagine trying to ignite 8 of those bastards simultaneously, imagine the vibration and lurching. The sad fact is that until SRB separation the shuttles SME’s do little more than counteract the ragged and asymmetrical nature of the thrust provided by those slugs. Why not just buy a license to build Enegia strap-on boosters from the Ukrainians and Russians and base an Orion tossing HLLV on them instead of those insane solids. Does anyone really want to trust the fate of a ship and 1000 nuclear pulse units to engines than cant be controlled or shut down? <br>
<br>
NASA is the worst example of a government agency gone fiscally mad. An example of this is the STS-112 mission that just ended. Tell me that spending  (not including launch costs) $385,000,000.00 for a truss and some radiators was worth the cost and I will bend over and kiss my own A…… Yes that’s right that’s what  NASA’s STS-112 just lifted to orbit and subsequently slapped on to the international corporate welfare station. <br>
<br>
NASA is no longer about the exploration of space, its real purpose seems to be the redistribution of tax dollars to aerospace corporations. Of late NASA’s most impressive deeds are not in the realm of space exploration but in the realm of absurd expenditures and creative accounting. <br>
<br>
To give NASA’s absurd cost of doing business some scale consider the fact that depending on who’s numbers you believe a  97,000 ton dual reactor Nimitz class aircraft carrier costs the same as 5-7 space shuttle launches. A 7000 ton guided missile destroyer costs the same as the little payload that  STS-112 just delivered to the  international corporate welfare station. <br>
<br>
The $30,000.00 a pound cost to LEO on the golden goose is not the only reason why few commercial satellites are launched with the it. Another reason is that the initial phase of the ride is so rough that the cost of building a satellite to take the pounding that those SRB’s dish out is prohibitive. It is much cheaper to let the Russians, French, or Chinese put the payloads up and that my friends is a sad state of affairs.<br>
<br>
As far as Orion is concerned NASA should never be allowed to control its development. That agency should be responsible only for crew training, technical assistance, launch facility preparation, non SRB based HLLV development and production, telemetry, mission tracking and control. I say that because if NASA were the senior agency they would gold plate the project to such a degree that the costs would be prohibitive. Los Alamos National laboratories in conjunction with Livermore National Laboratory should be the folks that hand out the contracts and be the body with oversight powers. It would also seem that Russian aerospace contractors should have an equal shot at the sub contracts because of their history of getting more bang for the buck. Remember we should be building a ‘space ship’ not another NASA gold plated diamond encrusted tin goose.<br>
